notes.text:
Updated krb5 packages that fix one security issue are now available for Red
Hat Enterprise Linux 3, 4, and 5.

The Red Hat Security Response Team has rated this update as having
important security impact. A Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS)
base score, which gives a detailed severity rating, is available from the
CVE link in the References section.
notes.title: Topic

notes.text:
Kerberos is a network authentication system which allows clients and
servers to authenticate to each other using symmetric encryption and a
trusted third party, the Key Distribution Center (KDC).

A NULL pointer dereference flaw was discovered in the MIT Kerberos Generic
Security Service Application Program Interface (GSS-API) library. A remote,
authenticated attacker could use this flaw to crash any server application
using the GSS-API authentication mechanism, by sending a specially-crafted
GSS-API token with a missing checksum field. (CVE-2010-1321)

Red Hat would like to thank the MIT Kerberos Team for responsibly reporting
this issue. Upstream acknowledges Shawn Emery of Oracle as the original
reporter.

All krb5 users should upgrade to these updated packages, which contain a
backported patch to correct this issue. All running services using the MIT
Kerberos libraries must be restarted for the update to take effect.

notes.text: The kg_accept_krb5 function in krb5/accept_sec_context.c in the GSS-API library in MIT Kerberos 5 (aka krb5) through 1.7.1 and 1.8 before 1.8.2, as used in kadmind and other applications, does not properly check for invalid GSS-API tokens, which allows remote authenticated users to cause a denial of service (NULL pointer dereference and daemon crash) via an AP-REQ message in which the authenticator's checksum field is missing.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: krb5: null pointer dereference in GSS-API library leads to DoS (MITKRB5-SA-2010-005)
notes.title: Vulnerability summary
